{"title_page": "Sandu Florea", "text_new": "{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = 10.15.11SanduFloreaByLuigiNovi1.jpg\n| caption       = Florea at the 2011 [[New York Comic Con]].\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = 28 June 1946 (age 73)\n| birth_place   = [[Ghelari]], [[Romania]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = [[Romania]]n, [[United States|American]]\n| area          = [[inker]], [[Comic book creator|writer]]\n| alias         =\n| notable works = ''[[Batman R.I.P.]]'', ''[[Batman: Battle for the Cowl]]'', ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer comics|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', ''[[The Executioner (book series)|The Executioner]]'', ''[[X-Men: The End]]''\n| awards        = [[Eurocon]] (1980)\n}}\n'''Sandu Florea''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8sandu \u02c8flore\u032fa}}; born 28 June 1946) is a [[Romanian-American]] [[comic book]] and [[comic strip]] [[Comic book creator|creator]], also known as an [[inker]] and [[Illustration|book illustrator]]. A trained architect and a presence on the [[science fiction]] scene during the 1970s, he became a professional in the [[comics]] genre with albums such as ''Galbar'', and was allegedly the only artist to have obtained a steady income in this way during the [[Communist Romania|communist period]]. A prolific contributor to Romanian children's magazines, Florea had his activity curbed by [[Censorship in Communist Romania|communist censorship]] when he first publicized his intention of emigrating to the United States. He eventually left the country shortly after the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989|1989 Revolution]], and soon after began collaborating with [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], [[DC Comics]] and other leading enterprises in the field of comic book publishing. He became especially noted for his activities as an inker, with contributions on series such as ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer comics|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', ''[[The Executioner (book series)|The Executioner]]'', ''[[X-Men: The End]]'', ''[[Batman R.I.P.]]'' and ''[[Batman: Battle for the Cowl]]''.\n\nFlorea has maintained enduring contacts with his native country, and has taken an initiative in popularizing the [[American comic book]] style in Romania. He has been described as one of the most successful among his colleagues, and claimed to be one of the most recognizable Romanians in his field.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career in Romania===\n[[File:Galbar Sandu Florea.jpg|thumb|left|Scene from ''Galbar'' (1973)]]\nBorn in [[Ghelari]], [[Hunedoara County]], Sandu Florea first became interested in comics while in fifth grade, his first contact with the medium being through a copy of the [[France|French]] youth magazine ''[[Pif gadget|Pif Vaillant]]''.<ref name=\"pccartoon\">{{in lang|ro}} Petrina Calabalic, [http://old.banateanul.ro/articol/ziar/timisoara/cartoon-man/4064/ \"Cartoon Man\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008123647/http://old.banateanul.ro/articol/ziar/timisoara/cartoon-man/4064/ |date=2011-10-08 }}, in ''[[B\u0103n\u0103\u0163eanul]]'', 6 December 2004</ref> This encounter, he recalled in a 2004 interview, left him with \"an impression that cannot be erased\", and \"the wish that I myself could draw such appealing and interesting characters.\"<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/>\n\nSandu Florea published his first comic strip in 1968, with ''Lumini\u0163a'' children's magazine. It was a series centered on the anecdotal hero classic ''[[P\u0103cal\u0103]]''.<ref name=\"icrartistul\">{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.icr.ro/sandu_florea ''Artistul Sandu Florea la Salonul European de Band\u0103 Desenat\u0103''], [[Romanian Cultural Institute]] release; retrieved 23 November 2011</ref> In 1971, Florea graduated from [[Bucharest]]'s [[Ion Mincu University of Architecture and Urbanism|Architectural College]], and subsequently worked for a building design institute in his adoptive city of [[Timi\u0219oara]].<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> Before graduation, he had also published his first work in the comics genre, inspired by the [[Folklore of Romania|folkloric tale]] of ''[[P\u0103cal\u0103]]'', and featured in a 1968 issue of ''Lumini\u0163a'' magazine.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/>\n\nAfter moving to Timi\u0219oara, he became a noted presence among the local [[science fiction]] fan base, joining the [[H. G. Wells]] Literary Club founded by writer Ovidiu \u015eurianu.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> Their collaboration produced the 1973 ''Galbar'', reportedly the first Romanian [[Science fiction comics|science fiction comic book]].<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\">{{in lang|ro}} [http://proscris.110mb.com/Ps13-14/florea13.htm \"Florea, Sandu\"], entry in [[Editura Nemira]]'s ''Dic\u0163ionar SF'', 1999 (republished by [http://proscris.110mb.com/ ''Pro-Scris''] [[webzine]]); retrieved 16 August 2009</ref> In 1975, he and Timi\u0219oara native Marcel Luca published what is thought to be the first-ever Romanian [[coloring book]] with a science fiction subject, ''Vreau s\u0103 fiu cosmonaut'' (\"I Want to be a [[Cosmonaut]]\"), which reputedly sold 45,000 copies.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> By then, having received offers of collaboration from two publishing houses ([[Editura Ion Creang\u0103]] and Editura Facla), Florea settled back in Bucharest and focused exclusively on his work in comics and illustration.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/><ref name=\"icrartistul\"/> Said to have been the most prolific comic book author active during the communist period, he had his work featured in almost all of the children's periodicals in print at the time.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\"/>\n\nDuring the late 1970s and early 1980s, he was creating and publishing comic books dedicated to popular legends, such as a retake on [[Ion Creang\u0103]]'s [[Fantasy literature|fantasy story]] ''[[Harap Alb]]'', or recounting episodes in [[History of Romania|Romanian history]] (involving [[Dacia]]n rulers [[Burebista]] and [[Decebalus]], [[Roman Emperor]] [[Trajan]],<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"cpbatman\">{{in lang|ro}} Cosmin Popan, [http://www.cotidianul.ro/batman_omorat_in_complicitate_cu_un_roman-65685.html \"Batman, omor\u00e2t \u00een complicitate cu un rom\u00e2n\"]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, in ''[[Cotidianul]]'', 26 November 2008</ref> and [[Wallachia]]n [[List of rulers of Wallachia|Prince]] [[Michael the Brave]]).<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/> Several single-issue albums in this category were based on texts by [[historical fiction]] author [[Radu Theodoru]], forming part of the series ''Str\u0103mo\u015fii'' (\"The Ancestors\").<ref name=\"sflambiek\">[http://lambiek.net/artists/f/florea_sandu.htm \"Sandu Florea (Romania)\"], entry in [[Lambiek]]'s [http://lambiek.net/artists/ ''Comiclopedia'']; retrieved 16 August 2009</ref> The full list includes: ''Cavalerul alb'' (\"The White Knight\"; Editura Facla, 1976), ''C\u0103lug\u0103reni'' (referencing the [[Battle of C\u0103lug\u0103reni]]; Editura Ion Creang\u0103, 1977), ''Misiune de sacrificiu'' (\"Suicidal Mission\"; Editura Ion Creang\u0103, 1979), ''\u00cen lumea lui Harap Alb'' (\"Inside Harap Alb's World\"; [[Editura Sport-Turism]], 1979), ''Burebista, regele dacilor'' (\"Burebista, King of the Dacians\"; Editura Sport-Turism, 1980), ''{{lang|ro|Decebal \u015fi Traian}}'' (\"Decebalus and Trajan\"; Editura Sport-Turism, 1981), ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'' (\"Carousel\"; Editura Sport-Turism, 1982), ''Sarmizegetusa eroic\u0103'' (\"Heroic [[Sarmizegetusa Regia|Sarmizegetusa]]\"; Editura Sport-Turism, 1983).<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/> Florea was also involved in creating Romania's own [[Western comics]], adapted from stories by Nicolae Fr\u00eenculescu.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/>\n\nThese works received critical attention, both in Romania and abroad. ''\u00cen lumea lui Harap Alb'' earned him the a [[Eurocon]] award (1980).<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"sflambiek\"/><ref name=\"mhpremiile\">{{in lang|ro}} [[Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103]], [http://www.observatorcultural.ro/FANTASY-SCIENCE-FICTION.-Premiile-care-au-fost*articleID_14094-articles_details.html \"Fantasy & Science Fiction. Premiile care au fost\"], in ''[[Observator Cultural]]'', Nr. 290, October 2005</ref> This, literary critic [[Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103]] notes, made Florea one in a final wave of Romanian Eurocon laureates to have emerged under communism (also including writers [[Vladimir Colin]], [[Ion Hobana]] and [[Gheorghe S\u0103s\u0103rman]]).<ref name=\"mhpremiile\"/>\n\nFlorea also received attention from celebrated poet [[Nichita St\u0103nescu]], who discovered in ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'' an unclassifiable and imaginative work. The writer argued: \"[Florea] introduces mystery where we usually had happy-endings, imagination where there was lyricism and an indecisive epic where there was nothing. The book he calls ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'' [...] is without precedent, in Romania and everywhere else.\"<ref name=\"poeziebd\">{{in lang|ro}} D. S., [http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-cultura-9933749-poezie-proiect-nichita-stanescu-sandu-florea-prinde-viata-muzeul-benzii-desenate.htm \"Poezie BD: un proiect Nichita St\u0103nescu \u2013 Sandu Florea prinde via\u0163\u0103 la Muzeul Benzii Desenate\"], [[Hotnews.ro]], 26 August 2011; retrieved 23 November 2011</ref> In 1982, St\u0103nescu began working with him on the album ''Semne \u015fi desemne'' (\"Signs and Designs\"). Florea printed the [[Lithography|lithographs]] to go with the poems, but the project was cut short when St\u0103nescu died (December 1983).<ref name=\"poeziebd\"/>\n\n===In the United States===\nThe 1984-1989 interval was described by Florea as \"one of the most difficult periods in my life.\"<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> Having unsuccessfully demanded from communist authorities the right of leaving for the United States, where two of his siblings had already settled, Florea was exposed to political persecution, and the [[Censorship in Communist Romania|censorship apparatus]] lifted his right to publish, prompting him to contribute several comic strips under various pseudonyms.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> He returned to public attention after the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989|1989 Revolution]], when he was briefly editor in chief of the new children's magazine ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}''.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"sflambiek\"/> With Fr\u00eenculescu, he also founded another such publication, called ''Proteus''.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\"/>\n\nSandu Florea, his wife and two children eventually left for the United States in 1991, moving to [[New York City]]<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> and afterward settling in [[Long Island]].<ref name=\"dnnautil\">{{in lang|ro}} Dodo Ni\u0163\u0103, [http://www.nautilus.nemira.ro/bd/batman-rip/ \"''Batman R.I.P.''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20090306185452/http://www.nautilus.nemira.ro/bd/batman-rip/ |date=2009-03-06 }}, in [[Editura Nemira]]'s ''Nautilus'', March 2009</ref> Although initially discouraged by the competition among comic book artists, Florea recounts, he decided to contact Marvel [[recruiter]]s within three months of his arrival, submitting a sample of his take on ''[[Conan the Barbarian (comics)|Conan the Barbarian]]''.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> According to his own statement, [[Conan the Barbarian|Conan]] proved compatible with his talents: \"[he was] the only Marvel character who did not fly, did not breathe fire and did not use psychic waves to defeat his enemies, being instead armed with a giant sword and axe. Since I had been drawing many historical tales back in the old country, Conan was a character whom I could depict in drawing with relative ease.\"<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/>\n\nHe was accepted by Marvel soon after this, specialized as an inker, and began working on several of its main releases, including, alongside ''Conan'', ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' and the various spin-offs of ''[[avengers (comics)|Avengers]]'', ''[[Blackwulf]]'', ''[[Elektra (comics)|Elektra]]'', ''[[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Mighty Thor]]'', ''[[Captain America]]'', ''[[Doctor Strange]]'', ''[[Fantastic Four]]'' and ''[[X-Men]]''.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"sflambiek\"/><ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> He also worked with [[DC Comics]] (on ''[[Superman (vol. 2)|Superman Second Series]]'',<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> ''[[Batman (comic book)|Batman]]'',<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/><ref name=\"cpbatman\"/><ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> ''[[Justice Society of America]]'', ''[[Nightwing]]'')<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> and [[Dark Horse Comics]],<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"cpbatman\"/> signing additional collaborations with [[Innovation Publishing]], Vivid Comics (on ''[[The Executioner (book series)|The Executioner]]'')<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/> and [[Chaos! Comics]] (''[[Lady Death]]'', ''[[Undertaker (comics)|Undertaker]]'').<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> Among the significant miniseries to which he contributed as an inker are ''[[X-Men: The End]]'' (2004\u20132006),<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> ''[[Batman R.I.P.]]'' (2008),<ref name=\"cpbatman\"/><ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> and ''[[Batman: Battle for the Cowl]]'' (2009).<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> His work with Dark Horse included ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer comics|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"sflambiek\"/><ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> and ''[[List of Angel comics|Angel]]''.<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> His artistic production also touched other media: Florea created [[storyboard]]s and other graphics for the motion picture producers [[Full Moon Features|Full Moon]], as well as book illustrations for ''[[The Princeton Review]]''.<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/>\n\n===2000s initiatives===\n[[File:10.15.11SanduFloreaByLuigiNovi2.jpg|thumb|Florea looking over an aspiring artist's portfolio at the 2011 New York Comic Con.]]\nFlorea was selected honorary president of the Romanian Association of Comic Book Fans in 2001.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/> Speaking in 2004, he expressed interest in relaunching the native comic book genre in his native country, and in publishing a new children's periodical with original content.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> In 2006, he participated in the relaunch of ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'', in a version argued by H\u0103ulic\u0103 to have been \"professional under any definition.\"<ref name=\"mhahbd\">{{in lang|ro}} [[Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103]], [http://www.observatorcultural.ro/FANTASY-SCIENCE-FICTION.-Ah-BD*articleID_15202-articles_details.html \"Fantasy & Science Fiction. Ah, BD!\"], in ''[[Observator Cultural]]'', Nr. 315, April 2006</ref>\n\nThe publication, which went out of print after only two issues due to distribution problems, included [[Romanian-language]] reprints of American comics such as ''Conan the Barbarian'' and ''[[Aliens (Dark Horse Comics publications)|Aliens]]'', alongside original collaborations between Florea and his Romanian colleagues: ''Dou\u0103 palo\u015fe'' (\"Two [[Backsword]]s\", with Florea as artist and Gy\u00f6rgy Gy\u00f6rfi-De\u00e1k as writer), ''Ultima frontier\u0103'' (\"The Final Frontier\", text by Florea, Marian Mirescu and Eddie Pandele, drawings by Daniel Rizea and C\u0103t\u0103lin Gospodin), ''Toxic'' (text by Florea, drawings by Tudor Popa), ''Leviathan'' (written by Cristian L\u0103z\u0103rescu, illustrated by Florea).<ref name=\"mhahbd\"/><ref name=\"mhbd\">{{in lang|ro}} [[Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103]], [http://www.observatorcultural.ro/FANTASY-SCIENCE-FICTION.-BD*articleID_13366-articles_details.html \"Fantasy & Science Fiction. BD\"], in ''[[Observator Cultural]]'', Nr. 273, June 2005</ref> The magazine also featured ''Borderland'', a comic series conceived especially for a Romanian public by writer [[John Warner (comics)|John Warner]] and illustrated by Florea, depicting the confrontation between three worlds: of the Mortals, of Magic and of the Demons.<ref name=\"mhbd\"/> Around the same time, Sandu Florea also began contributing to various Romanian [[webzine]]s, such as ''Pro-Scris'', ''Imagikon'' and ''Paradox''\u2014the latter of which published his strip ''Fort\u0103rea\u0163a'', based on a short story by Ovidiu Bufnil\u0103.<ref name=\"mhbd\"/> Several aspects related to the artist's new Romanian ventures were however criticized by Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103. He argued that ''Toxic'' in particular was \"weak and obvious\", and noted that, in its featured edition, the text of ''Borderland'' evidenced its translator's poor command of the Romanian language.<ref name=\"mhbd\"/>\n\nThese initiatives helped cement the artist's reputation in Romania. Sandu Florea claims to be \"The only Romanian professional graphic artist who has managed to make a living exclusively out of his drawings, in the old country as well as [...] in America.\"<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> Dodo Ni\u0163\u0103, a historiographer of Romanian comics and Florea's colleague at ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'',<ref name=\"mhbd\"/> placed ''\u00cen lumea lui Harap Alb'' as fifth among an all-time chart of original Romanian works in the genre.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} Ioana Calen, [http://www.cotidianul.ro/cartarescu_e_tras_in_banda_provocarea_desenata-12202.html \"C\u0103rt\u0103rescu e tras \u00een band\u0103 - Provocarea desenat\u0103\"]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, in ''[[Cotidianul]]'', 13 June 2006</ref> According to a 2008 piece in the Romanian daily ''[[Evenimentul Zilei]]'', Florea shares the distinction of \"best known Romanian comic book artist\" with [[Mircea Arapu]], the latter being known for his contribution in [[Franco-Belgian comics|Francophone comics]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} Adrian Grama, Vlad Stoicescu, [http://www.evz.ro/articole/detalii-articol/810028/Rahan-si-Pif-scapati-de-comunism/ \"Rahan \u015fi Pif, sc\u0103pa\u0163i de comunism\"], in ''[[Evenimentul Zilei]]'', 28 June 2008</ref>\n\nAn annual Romanian comic book [[fan convention]] in [[Constan\u0163a]] awards the Sandu Florea Prize to artists with a long contribution in their field.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/><ref>{{in lang|ro}} George Onofrei, [http://www.supliment.polirom.ro/article.aspx?article=4171 \"Lucian Amarii a c\u00ee\u015ftigat Premiul ''Sandu Florea'' pentru BD. JUP caut\u0103 pentru benzile desenate editori curajo\u015fi \u015fi f\u0103r\u0103 prejudec\u0103\u0163i\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090912224847/http://www.supliment.polirom.ro/article.aspx?article=4171 |date=2009-09-12 }}, in [[Polirom]]'s ''Suplimentul de Cultur\u0103'', Nr. 203, November 2008</ref> In 2010, Florea was guest of honor at the European Comic Strip Salon, organized by the [[Romanian Cultural Institute]] (ICR) at the [[National Theater Bucharest]].<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/> He exhibited his work, including the never before seen ''Semne \u015fi desemne'' collection, at the Bucharest \"Comic Book Museum\" exhibit, jointly organized by the ICR and the [[Belgian Comic Strip Center]] in 2011.<ref name=\"poeziebd\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://sanduflorea.com/ Official site]\n*{{gcdb|type=credit|search=Sandu+Florea|title=Sandu Florea}}\n*{{comicbookdb|type=creator|id=403|title=Sandu Florea}}\n*[http://proscris.110mb.com/Ps27-28/rusz27b.htm Contributions by and about Sandu Florea], in [http://proscris.110mb.com/ ''Pro-Scris''] [[webzine]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Florea, Sandu}}\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian descent]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Romanian architects]]\n[[Category:Romanian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Romanian comics artists]]\n[[Category:Romanian comics writers]]\n[[Category:Romanian lithographers]]\n[[Category:Romanian magazine founders]]\n[[Category:Comics inkers]]\n[[Category:People from Hunedoara County]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dacia in art]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = 10.15.11SanduFloreaByLuigiNovi1.jpg\n| caption       = Florea at the 2011 [[New York Comic Con]].\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = 28 June 1946 (age 73)\n| birth_place   = [[Ghelari]], [[Romania]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = [[Romania]]n, [[United States|American]]\n| area          = [[inker]], [[Comic book creator|writer]]\n| alias         =\n| notable works = ''[[Batman R.I.P.]]'', ''[[Batman: Battle for the Cowl]]'', ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer comics|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', ''[[The Executioner (book series)|The Executioner]]'', ''[[X-Men: The End]]''\n| awards        = [[Eurocon]] (1980)\n}}\n'''Sandu Florea''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8sandu \u02c8flore\u032fa}}; born 28 June 1946) is a [[Romanian-American]] [[comic book]] and [[comic strip]] [[Comic book creator|creator]], also known as an [[inker]] and [[Illustration|book illustrator]]. A trained architect and a presence on the [[science fiction]] scene during the 1970s, he became a professional in the [[comics]] genre with albums such as ''Galbar'', and was allegedly the only artist to have obtained a steady income in this way during the [[Communist Romania|communist period]]. A prolific contributor to Romanian children's magazines, Florea had his activity curbed by [[Censorship in Communist Romania|communist censorship]] when he first publicized his intention of emigrating to the United States. He eventually left the country shortly after the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989|1989 Revolution]], and soon after began collaborating with [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], [[DC Comics]] and other leading enterprises in the field of comic book publishing. He became especially noted for his activities as an inker, with contributions on series such as ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer comics|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', ''[[The Executioner (book series)|The Executioner]]'', ''[[X-Men: The End]]'', ''[[Batman R.I.P.]]'' and ''[[Batman: Battle for the Cowl]]''.\n\nFlorea has maintained enduring contacts with his native country, and has taken an initiative in popularizing the [[American comic book]] style in Romania. He has been described as one of the most successful among his colleagues, and claimed to be one of the most recognizable Romanians in his field.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career in Romania===\n[[File:Galbar Sandu Florea.jpg|thumb|left|Scene from ''Galbar'' (1973)]]\nBorn in [[Ghelari]], [[Hunedoara County]], Sandu Florea first became interested in comics while in fifth grade, his first contact with the medium being through a copy of the [[France|French]] youth magazine ''[[Pif gadget|Pif Vaillant]]''.<ref name=\"pccartoon\">{{in lang|ro}} Petrina Calabalic, [http://old.banateanul.ro/articol/ziar/timisoara/cartoon-man/4064/ \"Cartoon Man\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008123647/http://old.banateanul.ro/articol/ziar/timisoara/cartoon-man/4064/ |date=2011-10-08 }}, in ''[[B\u0103n\u0103\u0163eanul]]'', 6 December 2004</ref> This encounter, he recalled in a 2004 interview, left him with \"an impression that cannot be erased\", and \"the wish that I myself could draw such appealing and interesting characters.\"<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/>\n\nSandu Florea published his first comic strip in 1968, with ''Lumini\u0163a'' children's magazine. It was a series centered on the anecdotal hero classic ''[[P\u0103cal\u0103]]''.<ref name=\"icrartistul\">{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.icr.ro/sandu_florea ''Artistul Sandu Florea la Salonul European de Band\u0103 Desenat\u0103''], [[Romanian Cultural Institute]] release; retrieved 23 November 2011</ref> In 1971, Florea graduated from [[Bucharest]]'s [[Ion Mincu University of Architecture and Urbanism|Architectural College]], and subsequently worked for a building design institute in his adoptive city of [[Timi\u015foara]].<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> Before graduation, he had also published his first work in the comics genre, inspired by the [[Folklore of Romania|folkloric tale]] of ''[[P\u0103cal\u0103]]'', and featured in a 1968 issue of ''Lumini\u0163a'' magazine.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/>\n\nAfter moving to Timi\u015foara, he became a noted presence among the local [[science fiction]] fan base, joining the [[H. G. Wells]] Literary Club founded by writer Ovidiu \u015eurianu.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> Their collaboration produced the 1973 ''Galbar'', reportedly the first Romanian [[Science fiction comics|science fiction comic book]].<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\">{{in lang|ro}} [http://proscris.110mb.com/Ps13-14/florea13.htm \"Florea, Sandu\"], entry in [[Editura Nemira]]'s ''Dic\u0163ionar SF'', 1999 (republished by [http://proscris.110mb.com/ ''Pro-Scris''] [[webzine]]); retrieved 16 August 2009</ref> In 1975, he and Timi\u015foara native Marcel Luca published what is thought to be the first-ever Romanian [[coloring book]] with a science fiction subject, ''Vreau s\u0103 fiu cosmonaut'' (\"I Want to be a [[Cosmonaut]]\"), which reputedly sold 45,000 copies.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> By then, having received offers of collaboration from two publishing houses ([[Editura Ion Creang\u0103]] and Editura Facla), Florea settled back in Bucharest and focused exclusively on his work in comics and illustration.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/><ref name=\"icrartistul\"/> Said to have been the most prolific comic book author active during the communist period, he had his work featured in almost all of the children's periodicals in print at the time.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\"/>\n\nDuring the late 1970s and early 1980s, he was creating and publishing comic books dedicated to popular legends, such as a retake on [[Ion Creang\u0103]]'s [[Fantasy literature|fantasy story]] ''[[Harap Alb]]'', or recounting episodes in [[History of Romania|Romanian history]] (involving [[Dacia]]n rulers [[Burebista]] and [[Decebalus]], [[Roman Emperor]] [[Trajan]],<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"cpbatman\">{{in lang|ro}} Cosmin Popan, [http://www.cotidianul.ro/batman_omorat_in_complicitate_cu_un_roman-65685.html \"Batman, omor\u00e2t \u00een complicitate cu un rom\u00e2n\"]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, in ''[[Cotidianul]]'', 26 November 2008</ref> and [[Wallachia]]n [[List of rulers of Wallachia|Prince]] [[Michael the Brave]]).<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/> Several single-issue albums in this category were based on texts by [[historical fiction]] author [[Radu Theodoru]], forming part of the series ''Str\u0103mo\u015fii'' (\"The Ancestors\").<ref name=\"sflambiek\">[http://lambiek.net/artists/f/florea_sandu.htm \"Sandu Florea (Romania)\"], entry in [[Lambiek]]'s [http://lambiek.net/artists/ ''Comiclopedia'']; retrieved 16 August 2009</ref> The full list includes: ''Cavalerul alb'' (\"The White Knight\"; Editura Facla, 1976), ''C\u0103lug\u0103reni'' (referencing the [[Battle of C\u0103lug\u0103reni]]; Editura Ion Creang\u0103, 1977), ''Misiune de sacrificiu'' (\"Suicidal Mission\"; Editura Ion Creang\u0103, 1979), ''\u00cen lumea lui Harap Alb'' (\"Inside Harap Alb's World\"; [[Editura Sport-Turism]], 1979), ''Burebista, regele dacilor'' (\"Burebista, King of the Dacians\"; Editura Sport-Turism, 1980), ''{{lang|ro|Decebal \u015fi Traian}}'' (\"Decebalus and Trajan\"; Editura Sport-Turism, 1981), ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'' (\"Carousel\"; Editura Sport-Turism, 1982), ''Sarmizegetusa eroic\u0103'' (\"Heroic [[Sarmizegetusa Regia|Sarmizegetusa]]\"; Editura Sport-Turism, 1983).<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/> Florea was also involved in creating Romania's own [[Western comics]], adapted from stories by Nicolae Fr\u00eenculescu.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/>\n\nThese works received critical attention, both in Romania and abroad. ''\u00cen lumea lui Harap Alb'' earned him the a [[Eurocon]] award (1980).<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"sflambiek\"/><ref name=\"mhpremiile\">{{in lang|ro}} [[Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103]], [http://www.observatorcultural.ro/FANTASY-SCIENCE-FICTION.-Premiile-care-au-fost*articleID_14094-articles_details.html \"Fantasy & Science Fiction. Premiile care au fost\"], in ''[[Observator Cultural]]'', Nr. 290, October 2005</ref> This, literary critic [[Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103]] notes, made Florea one in a final wave of Romanian Eurocon laureates to have emerged under communism (also including writers [[Vladimir Colin]], [[Ion Hobana]] and [[Gheorghe S\u0103s\u0103rman]]).<ref name=\"mhpremiile\"/>\n\nFlorea also received attention from celebrated poet [[Nichita St\u0103nescu]], who discovered in ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'' an unclassifiable and imaginative work. The writer argued: \"[Florea] introduces mystery where we usually had happy-endings, imagination where there was lyricism and an indecisive epic where there was nothing. The book he calls ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'' [...] is without precedent, in Romania and everywhere else.\"<ref name=\"poeziebd\">{{in lang|ro}} D. S., [http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-cultura-9933749-poezie-proiect-nichita-stanescu-sandu-florea-prinde-viata-muzeul-benzii-desenate.htm \"Poezie BD: un proiect Nichita St\u0103nescu \u2013 Sandu Florea prinde via\u0163\u0103 la Muzeul Benzii Desenate\"], [[Hotnews.ro]], 26 August 2011; retrieved 23 November 2011</ref> In 1982, St\u0103nescu began working with him on the album ''Semne \u015fi desemne'' (\"Signs and Designs\"). Florea printed the [[Lithography|lithographs]] to go with the poems, but the project was cut short when St\u0103nescu died (December 1983).<ref name=\"poeziebd\"/>\n\n===In the United States===\nThe 1984-1989 interval was described by Florea as \"one of the most difficult periods in my life.\"<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> Having unsuccessfully demanded from communist authorities the right of leaving for the United States, where two of his siblings had already settled, Florea was exposed to political persecution, and the [[Censorship in Communist Romania|censorship apparatus]] lifted his right to publish, prompting him to contribute several comic strips under various pseudonyms.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> He returned to public attention after the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989|1989 Revolution]], when he was briefly editor in chief of the new children's magazine ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}''.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"sflambiek\"/> With Fr\u00eenculescu, he also founded another such publication, called ''Proteus''.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\"/>\n\nSandu Florea, his wife and two children eventually left for the United States in 1991, moving to [[New York City]]<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> and afterward settling in [[Long Island]].<ref name=\"dnnautil\">{{in lang|ro}} Dodo Ni\u0163\u0103, [http://www.nautilus.nemira.ro/bd/batman-rip/ \"''Batman R.I.P.''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20090306185452/http://www.nautilus.nemira.ro/bd/batman-rip/ |date=2009-03-06 }}, in [[Editura Nemira]]'s ''Nautilus'', March 2009</ref> Although initially discouraged by the competition among comic book artists, Florea recounts, he decided to contact Marvel [[recruiter]]s within three months of his arrival, submitting a sample of his take on ''[[Conan the Barbarian (comics)|Conan the Barbarian]]''.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> According to his own statement, [[Conan the Barbarian|Conan]] proved compatible with his talents: \"[he was] the only Marvel character who did not fly, did not breathe fire and did not use psychic waves to defeat his enemies, being instead armed with a giant sword and axe. Since I had been drawing many historical tales back in the old country, Conan was a character whom I could depict in drawing with relative ease.\"<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/>\n\nHe was accepted by Marvel soon after this, specialized as an inker, and began working on several of its main releases, including, alongside ''Conan'', ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' and the various spin-offs of ''[[avengers (comics)|Avengers]]'', ''[[Blackwulf]]'', ''[[Elektra (comics)|Elektra]]'', ''[[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Mighty Thor]]'', ''[[Captain America]]'', ''[[Doctor Strange]]'', ''[[Fantastic Four]]'' and ''[[X-Men]]''.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/><ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"sflambiek\"/><ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> He also worked with [[DC Comics]] (on ''[[Superman (vol. 2)|Superman Second Series]]'',<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> ''[[Batman (comic book)|Batman]]'',<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/><ref name=\"cpbatman\"/><ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> ''[[Justice Society of America]]'', ''[[Nightwing]]'')<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> and [[Dark Horse Comics]],<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"cpbatman\"/> signing additional collaborations with [[Innovation Publishing]], Vivid Comics (on ''[[The Executioner (book series)|The Executioner]]'')<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/> and [[Chaos! Comics]] (''[[Lady Death]]'', ''[[Undertaker (comics)|Undertaker]]'').<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> Among the significant miniseries to which he contributed as an inker are ''[[X-Men: The End]]'' (2004\u20132006),<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> ''[[Batman R.I.P.]]'' (2008),<ref name=\"cpbatman\"/><ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> and ''[[Batman: Battle for the Cowl]]'' (2009).<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> His work with Dark Horse included ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer comics|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''<ref name=\"sfnemira\"/><ref name=\"sflambiek\"/><ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> and ''[[List of Angel comics|Angel]]''.<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/> His artistic production also touched other media: Florea created [[storyboard]]s and other graphics for the motion picture producers [[Full Moon Features|Full Moon]], as well as book illustrations for ''[[The Princeton Review]]''.<ref name=\"dnnautil\"/>\n\n===2000s initiatives===\n[[File:10.15.11SanduFloreaByLuigiNovi2.jpg|thumb|Florea looking over an aspiring artist's portfolio at the 2011 New York Comic Con.]]\nFlorea was selected honorary president of the Romanian Association of Comic Book Fans in 2001.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/> Speaking in 2004, he expressed interest in relaunching the native comic book genre in his native country, and in publishing a new children's periodical with original content.<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> In 2006, he participated in the relaunch of ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'', in a version argued by H\u0103ulic\u0103 to have been \"professional under any definition.\"<ref name=\"mhahbd\">{{in lang|ro}} [[Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103]], [http://www.observatorcultural.ro/FANTASY-SCIENCE-FICTION.-Ah-BD*articleID_15202-articles_details.html \"Fantasy & Science Fiction. Ah, BD!\"], in ''[[Observator Cultural]]'', Nr. 315, April 2006</ref>\n\nThe publication, which went out of print after only two issues due to distribution problems, included [[Romanian-language]] reprints of American comics such as ''Conan the Barbarian'' and ''[[Aliens (Dark Horse Comics publications)|Aliens]]'', alongside original collaborations between Florea and his Romanian colleagues: ''Dou\u0103 palo\u015fe'' (\"Two [[Backsword]]s\", with Florea as artist and Gy\u00f6rgy Gy\u00f6rfi-De\u00e1k as writer), ''Ultima frontier\u0103'' (\"The Final Frontier\", text by Florea, Marian Mirescu and Eddie Pandele, drawings by Daniel Rizea and C\u0103t\u0103lin Gospodin), ''Toxic'' (text by Florea, drawings by Tudor Popa), ''Leviathan'' (written by Cristian L\u0103z\u0103rescu, illustrated by Florea).<ref name=\"mhahbd\"/><ref name=\"mhbd\">{{in lang|ro}} [[Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103]], [http://www.observatorcultural.ro/FANTASY-SCIENCE-FICTION.-BD*articleID_13366-articles_details.html \"Fantasy & Science Fiction. BD\"], in ''[[Observator Cultural]]'', Nr. 273, June 2005</ref> The magazine also featured ''Borderland'', a comic series conceived especially for a Romanian public by writer [[John Warner (comics)|John Warner]] and illustrated by Florea, depicting the confrontation between three worlds: of the Mortals, of Magic and of the Demons.<ref name=\"mhbd\"/> Around the same time, Sandu Florea also began contributing to various Romanian [[webzine]]s, such as ''Pro-Scris'', ''Imagikon'' and ''Paradox''\u2014the latter of which published his strip ''Fort\u0103rea\u0163a'', based on a short story by Ovidiu Bufnil\u0103.<ref name=\"mhbd\"/> Several aspects related to the artist's new Romanian ventures were however criticized by Michael H\u0103ulic\u0103. He argued that ''Toxic'' in particular was \"weak and obvious\", and noted that, in its featured edition, the text of ''Borderland'' evidenced its translator's poor command of the Romanian language.<ref name=\"mhbd\"/>\n\nThese initiatives helped cement the artist's reputation in Romania. Sandu Florea claims to be \"The only Romanian professional graphic artist who has managed to make a living exclusively out of his drawings, in the old country as well as [...] in America.\"<ref name=\"pccartoon\"/> Dodo Ni\u0163\u0103, a historiographer of Romanian comics and Florea's colleague at ''{{lang|ro|Carusel}}'',<ref name=\"mhbd\"/> placed ''\u00cen lumea lui Harap Alb'' as fifth among an all-time chart of original Romanian works in the genre.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} Ioana Calen, [http://www.cotidianul.ro/cartarescu_e_tras_in_banda_provocarea_desenata-12202.html \"C\u0103rt\u0103rescu e tras \u00een band\u0103 - Provocarea desenat\u0103\"]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, in ''[[Cotidianul]]'', 13 June 2006</ref> According to a 2008 piece in the Romanian daily ''[[Evenimentul Zilei]]'', Florea shares the distinction of \"best known Romanian comic book artist\" with [[Mircea Arapu]], the latter being known for his contribution in [[Franco-Belgian comics|Francophone comics]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} Adrian Grama, Vlad Stoicescu, [http://www.evz.ro/articole/detalii-articol/810028/Rahan-si-Pif-scapati-de-comunism/ \"Rahan \u015fi Pif, sc\u0103pa\u0163i de comunism\"], in ''[[Evenimentul Zilei]]'', 28 June 2008</ref>\n\nAn annual Romanian comic book [[fan convention]] in [[Constan\u0163a]] awards the Sandu Florea Prize to artists with a long contribution in their field.<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/><ref>{{in lang|ro}} George Onofrei, [http://www.supliment.polirom.ro/article.aspx?article=4171 \"Lucian Amarii a c\u00ee\u015ftigat Premiul ''Sandu Florea'' pentru BD. JUP caut\u0103 pentru benzile desenate editori curajo\u015fi \u015fi f\u0103r\u0103 prejudec\u0103\u0163i\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090912224847/http://www.supliment.polirom.ro/article.aspx?article=4171 |date=2009-09-12 }}, in [[Polirom]]'s ''Suplimentul de Cultur\u0103'', Nr. 203, November 2008</ref> In 2010, Florea was guest of honor at the European Comic Strip Salon, organized by the [[Romanian Cultural Institute]] (ICR) at the [[National Theater Bucharest]].<ref name=\"icrartistul\"/> He exhibited his work, including the never before seen ''Semne \u015fi desemne'' collection, at the Bucharest \"Comic Book Museum\" exhibit, jointly organized by the ICR and the [[Belgian Comic Strip Center]] in 2011.<ref name=\"poeziebd\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://sanduflorea.com/ Official site]\n*{{gcdb|type=credit|search=Sandu+Florea|title=Sandu Florea}}\n*{{comicbookdb|type=creator|id=403|title=Sandu Florea}}\n*[http://proscris.110mb.com/Ps27-28/rusz27b.htm Contributions by and about Sandu Florea], in [http://proscris.110mb.com/ ''Pro-Scris''] [[webzine]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Florea, Sandu}}\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian descent]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Romanian architects]]\n[[Category:Romanian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Romanian comics artists]]\n[[Category:Romanian comics writers]]\n[[Category:Romanian lithographers]]\n[[Category:Romanian magazine founders]]\n[[Category:Comics inkers]]\n[[Category:People from Hunedoara County]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dacia in art]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Timi\u0219oara(viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandu_Florea"}
